4) Area chart - Similar to a line chart, but with the addition of color. Area charts can be used to show cumulative totals, stacked data, and trends. 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
 # Data days = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] 
sales = [100, 200, 150, 300, 250] 
# Create area chart
 plt.fill_between(days, sales, color="skyblue", alpha=0.5) 
# Line on top (optional)
 plt.plot(days, sales, color="blue")
 # Labels and Title
 plt.xlabel("Days")
 plt.ylabel("Sales")
 plt.title("Area Chart Example")
 # Show graph 
plt.show() 

5) Scatter plot -A chart that uses dots to represent values for two different numeric variables.
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
 x = [2, 4, 6, 8] # Study hours
 y = [50, 65, 80, 90] # Marks
 plt.scatter(x, y)
 plt.xlabel("Study Hours")
 plt.ylabel("Marks") 
plt.title("Scatter Plot Example") 
plt.show()

6) Bubble chart - A chart that displays multiple data points and their relationships.
 import matplotlib.pyplot as plt 
# Data 
x = [2, 4, 6, 8] # Study Hours
 y = [50, 65, 80, 90] # Marks
 size = [200, 400, 600, 800]
 # Bubble size (Attendance) 
# Create Bubble Chart 
plt.scatter(x, y, s=size) 
# Labels and Title 
plt.xlabel("Study Hours") 
plt.ylabel("Marks")
 plt.title("Bubble Chart Example")
 # Show chart 
plt.show() 

